<Author>rtworldtraveller
<Content>not there yet. after staying and dining at all the 5 star hotels in hong kong over the years, i decided its time to check out the new four seasons hotel in hk. i've heard conflicting comments from friends of mine who have stayed at the property during the past year. the lobby area is kinda sparse, with not much of a focal point. the check in and concierge counters were off to the side and the low ceilings kinda make the area feel cramped (as the lobby has a 4 storey height to it).service was quick, efficient but was cold and without much of a four seasons touch. its as if they are there to get you in and out asap... maybe thats how they want it to be seen - an efficient biz type like hotel - again, this is not a four seasons trait. the other better four seasons that i've stayed in, offers a gracious charm to it, efficient but filled with care and warmth. diligent attention and an opening to get u what u want and beyond that, get u who u didn't know u want. fs george v in paris does that so well. thats the benchmark of all four seasons should be compared to.room was alright, a bright blend of east and west, views were quite good, if its a clear day, otherwise, u'll be looking out to a grey harbor. the funny thing is that the apartment block next to the hotel, which i understand is also managed by the four seasons in hk, offers much better harbor views. rooms at the apartment block faces more towards the central and causeway bay direction, while the hotel block faces more towards tsim sha tsui west and the macau ferry terminal. if you are looking for the room with the best harbor view from hong kong side, this is not it. the harbor view rooms at the grand hyatt, shangri-la, conrad offers better views.i checked out the dining facilities at the hotel during the stay and had dinner at both the french and chinese restaurant. since the executive chef at the caprice came from le cing of george v paris, i expect a great meal. alas, that was not the case. quite disappointed is my feeling. service was like the check in - fast and furious. its as if they were trying to outdo each other in trying to get the table turned. saw a waiter breaking some glasses that was placed in the long glass cabinet placed in the middle of the restaurant. the rush rush rush feel doesn't do it for me in a french restaurant, especially with staff from george v paris running the place. i spoke to the manager of the restaurant and made him aware of my observations and he concurred. he is definitely not happy with the level of service being offered. as for the food, i'm a frequent guest at le cinq, and the food at caprice is not a true reflection of what it is in paris. guess something has lost itself in the translation of the cooking. i understand that the executive chef from le cinq visited the restarurant a while back and was quite disappointed with the level of food. efforts have been made to rectify that problem but i still don't see it as even offering the best french fine dining in hong kong. gaddi's at the pen is still the best in this aspect. so much for my french fine dining.the chinese restaurant was modern, silverish grey in color and a bit cold. just like most of the staff at the hotel, the four seasons touch just doesn't show itself. one thing i've noticed is that many of the staff seems to be a bit distance and acting cool. thats again, not a four seasons trait - cool is just not four seasons. four seasons is all about warmth, openess, and willingness to aid and get the guest feeling top of the world.food at the chinese restaurant came in pretty dainty size offerings, doesn't make the dining experience that great, as i was with a group of friends that all made comments that we need to double what we ordered. guess thats what management decided to go with. again, i was disappointed with the chinese food, as i can get much better fare at many great chinese restauratns in hong kong. if one needs just to entertain in central, i guess fs hk is an alright choice. if u need to entertain with great food, this is not the place to go.the swimming pool area was pretty nice (located at and angle facing tsim sha tsui and wanchai), especially at nite and deserted. the shimmering lights of hong kong harbor and kowloon is always great to check out. for any travellers with friends with american club membership, u should check out the nite scene of hk from the club's city location - located in side 2 exchange square, 49th floor).all in all, fs hk is a middle of the road four seasons, with much lacking befitting a city like hong kong. it doesn't come close to the other great four seasons around the world. i place it on the same level as the four seasons in singapore and sydney, albeit in a brand spanking new building. and way way behind the four seasons flagship, four season george v paris. 
