<Author>JChua
<Content>Loved brand new hotels! Spent two wonderful nights (09-11 Feb) at the new Four Seasons Hotel. Booked it since we loved staying at brand new hotels and it was having a promotion with free HK$500 dinning vouchers at its restaurants. Having stayed at various hotels in Kowloon side - The Peninsula, Intercontinental (both with superb views of the Victoria Harbour), Marco Polo, and Hong Kong Island side - Harbour View Renaissance, I would vote this new Hotel to be among the very best in Hong Kong at this present moment (early 2006). This was our first stay at a Four Seasons Hotel. We had found its huge lobby somewhat under-furnished, as some 4 or 5 stars hotels we had been to had nicer looking lobby than theirs. We found lobbies to be very important to a hotel's reputation as well as status as they always say, 'First impresssion counts'! The other minor fault is the mini TV above the bath, the height of the TV somewhat makes lying down in the tub difficult to watch .......they should have adjusted the TV lower. Another not mentioned point about the location of this hotel is - the MTR (subway) of this hotel (the Hong Kong station) actually DOES NOT connect with the rest of the MTR lines/stations of Hong Kong! Although this is of no fault of the Hotel, you would have to walk a good 10-15 minutes from the Central Station (where the train last stops) to the Hotel. Though the long walk was in air-conditioned comfort and sometimes even with the ease of travellators, I had to say that it is rather tiring especially after a whole day of shopping and walking. Room wise, we had a Deluxe Harbour View room which had the MOST COMFORTABLE hotel bed we ever slept on! The 42 inch Plasma TV, nice harbour views of Kowloon side (although a far cry compared to views from the Peninsula or the Intercontinental) , floor to wall yellow marbled bathroom, huge bathroom etc, were all very nice indeed. But it somewhat reminded us of the Grand Hyatt....Even the location, within the massive IFC Mall, is similar to the Grand Hyatt in Beijing, China, which was connected to the Far East Shopping Plaza. Great for shopping, I would say, moreover, with a good supermarket called the 'City Super' in the IFC Mall.The Hotel's service staff, like the posters here had said, are all very very well trained. They are courteous, obliging, and not at all snotty (with the exception of 1 or 2 snotty ones at the expensive and classy Lung Keng Heen Chinese restaurant on level 4). On checkout, they made a mistake of charging us one minibar item which we swear did not consume, and the reception lady graciously cancelled it - no questions asked! They even went the extra mile for their guests, by providing turn down service, free large-sized Perssimons (a very nice fruit) and free shuttle to and fro the Airport Express train service at the IFC Mall. Though the distance covered is short, you might find lugging all your luggages up and down escalators within the massive IFC Mall, both trying and tiring! Simply ask and they would provide this wonderful service. All in all, stay here if you do not mind splurging or see if they have a promotion going on. Without promotion, our room would have cost us a whopping HK$4,100 plus tax plus service (about US$600 a night). Or else, stay here if you have business to do in the Central District of the Hong Kong Island, or are travelling to and fro to Macau, the outlying islands, Disneyland (direct MTR train service), great shopping at the IFC Mall, convenience to and fro the Hong Kong Airport. Although a great stay with many nice conveniences, we would only rate this new Four Seasons as a top end of a good 5 stars Hotel, certainly not a 6 stars. 
